post.author: bpanjavan
post.title: Silverlight 3 Unit Testing - The GameBoard
post.content:
Last time I went over the setup of Unit Testing in Silverlight, which is fundamentally not any different from conventional Unit Testing.

This time we're going to use Test-Driven Development to build a Silverlight 3 Class Library for The GameBoard.

 

We start with the requirements

 Below are the requirements drawn right off the top of my head.  I've also done some OO analysis by bolding the most prominent tangible objects and italicizing the verbs that act on them.

 "A gameboard is a flat plane divided by even sized square spaces.  The gameboard is used to host a game / match between 2 or more teams.  For this scope, we will create gameboard that we can add pieces to and not yet be concerned about teams or the game / match.  Pieces can be moved from space to space.  2 pieces can NOT occupy the same space at the same time."

 

Applying Test-Driven Development

In the previous step, we setup our class library and test project.  Our GameBoardTests class included a test that always passes.

 

Let's wipe out this test and write a real test that will test the initialization of our GameBoard. We're using the Factory Design Pattern to create a GameBoardFactory instance.  Then we call CreateGameBoard and expect to get an instance of interface type IGameBoard.

 

"But that won't even compile..."  Right. It won't.  That's the first principle behind Test-Driven Development.  We plan and write out our test code BEFORE we write the actual code.  Attempt to compile this and we'll fail spectacularly.  The next step is to add the BARE MINIMUM of what we need to compile.

We add our factory and our interface to the project.

 

Next, we implement the method that we attempted to call in our Unit Test.  Remember, implement the BARE MINIMUM.  Also note, we've added a reference to the class library in our test project, and a reference to System.Collections.Generic since our GameBoardFactory constructor takes in a generic Dictionary.

 

Now run our test project.  If I hadn't mentioned it before, the quickest way to do this is to right click on the .HTML page in our test project and click "View In Browser".

 

As you can see our test failed.  We could've made it pass but this was done on purpose.  Another principle of Test-Driven Development is that you should ALWAYS make your tests fail before you make them pass.  This seems a little mundane but the point is to prove to yourself that your tests are capable of failing.  Besides you'll get a good feeling from "fixing" failed tests and watching them go from red to green. 

Let's fix this test the right way. I'm going to add my GameBoardBase class, which implements my IGame interface.

 

I'm also going to fix the GameBoardFactory to actually return what it is supposed to.

 

Then we re-run our test application to see the results.

 

This process is iterative.  I'll quickly go through one more example.  My gameboard should have a varying number of spaces dependent on what I pass into my settings.  But if I don't pass anything in I expect my GameBoard to default to 5 spaces wide by 5 spaces long.  Here's what the test looks like.

 

Once again we've written something that doesn't compile, so let's do the BARE MINIMUM to make it do so.  We add the properties to IGameBoard and implement them in GameBoardBase.

 

This test will fail when you run it, just as expected.  As the cycle calls for, we implement what we need to pass this test by setting the values of these properties appropriately in GameBoardBase.

 

After fixing this test, you should be back to all green when you run your tests again.  The cycle repeats until you've covered all of your requirements.

  1. Write the test (which may or may not compile)

  2. Do the BARE MINIMUM to compile your test

  3. "Red Light" - Run your test and fail.  If it's not failing yet, you've either implemented too much, or your test isn't strict enough.

  4. "Fix" your test.  Do the BARE MINIMUM to make it pass.

  5. "Green Light" - Re-run your test and get it to pass.  After which, repeat step 1.

The full code sample, including all of my Unit Tests for this project can be found here.

comment.content: A speaker is definitely an electronic device that is created to convert electrical signals into sound. As you know, with out speakers, the fanciest audio gear would be useless. The speaker does its job by vibrating very much like a drum. The "drum" in this instance frequently piece of paper, fabric or plastic attached along its total edge to a circular metal frame. This composes the front from your speaker and is referred to as the "cone" or "diaphragm". Just like a drum, the cone makes sound by moving back and forth really rapidly. This motion is created by a coil which is attached towards the inner element of the cone. The metal coil is attached to the stereo or CD player's wires as well cone/coil assembly is situated in front of a magnet.

These borders are common place for DVD movies and depending on the DVD recording, may give you the option of Full Screen or Wide Screen formats.
